In this blog, I will be explaining how to leverage ghidra scripts to decrypt the
encrypted strings in a binary.
Malware authors store the crical strings/shellcode in the .data or. rdata
secon of the binary in encrypted format to evade detecon. Furthermore, the
characters of the strings are stored as the array of characters to make the stac

This was part of one of the challenges from Hack the box named “Lockpick3.0”
(a sample wrien based out of Locky Ransomware) in which a memory image
has been obtained from a ransomware aected ubuntu machine. The malicious
binary which aected the machine has been retrieved.
On analysing the binary, XOR decrypon loop for more than 10 strings have
been observed. This XOR decrypon results in the URL for command-and-

Looking at the mulple calls to FUN_001029ca with dierent addresses from

The decrypon loop XORs each byte of the input with a corresponding key.
Looking at the overwhelming amount of the encrypted strings in the binary, I
have decided to write a ghidra script that takes address, size of the string and
key as a parameter and return the corresponding string in the ascii format and
was able to successfully retrieve the strings within no me.
The code can be downloaded from the GitHub link
hps://github.com/vadhyar/Reverse_engineering/blob/master/strings_decryp

On decrypng the bytes at one of the addresses,
Script in Acon:
 Copy the code in the ghidra’s Script manager
 Run the script
 Script prompts to enter the address of the array, size of the array and the
key to decrypt.
 Looking at the ghidra’s script console, we can observe that the string
has been decrypted and provided in the ascii format
This script makes it easier to obtain the deobfuscated/decrypted form of the
strings in the binary.
Conclusion: Ghidra Scripts always comes handy when working with samples
with mulple obfuscaon loops. This reduces the me consumpon for
deobfuscaon and saves me for further analysis.
A similar technique of Mulple XOR encrypons is seen in ransomwares like
